Question: Does Sandvik see the likely recession as a potential barrier for its sustainability activity? #InnovationforSustainability #SandvikIdeasHub #WazokuPlatform

"Sustainability is everyone's problem but also everyone's opportunity" - @MatsWLundberg 

The ideas hub powered by the Wazoku platform has enabled everyone from all parts of the organisation to engage in the process and collaborate

#Innovationforsustainability

"Handling our internal processes and then engaging with suppliers about their sustainability targets, strategies, and outcomes. We're putting the impetus on them to innovate alongside us for the good of the whole system."- Mats W Lundberg 

#InnovationforSustainability

What is circularity? -> It means that a product is created with its own end-of-life taken into account. In a circular economy, once the user is finished with the product, it goes back into the supply chain instead of the landfill.

"With a circularity shift, you turn this into a circle: getting R&D to talk to the end-of-life planners so teams are more mindful, innovative, and forward-thinking."

- Mats W Lundberg

#InnovationforSustainability #SandvikIdeasHub #WazokuPlatform
"Traditionally, companies have a linear sense of thinking: you invent something, produce it, and then it's gone."

Key takeaway #1: "For sustainability you need to understand the entire supply chain and the system perspective." - Mats W Lundberg

#InnovationforSustainability #SandvikIdeasHub #WazokuPlatform

If the annual wage gap were eliminated, a Latina working in the U.S would have enough money to pay for approximately: the total cost of tuition and fees for a two-year college; nearly 38 more months of child care; or nearly 20 additional months of health insurance premiums.

When analyzing with an intersectional lens, we see this issue persists beyond gender. Latina women also make approx. 20% less than their white woman counterparts, 8% less than their Black woman counterparts, and 3% less than their Indigenous American counterparts.

Today is Latina Equal Pay Day. More than 50 years after the passage of the Equal Pay Act of 1963, Latinas typically earn only 57 cents for every dollar earned by white, non-Hispanic men and must work nearly 23 months to make what white men earn in 12 months. https://t.co/HTSdp0taxB
